
He was mocking me.
Toivo, just to prove he was the dominant male, lurched at Yuuhi. The vampire yelped and fled down the steps, and, satisfied with himself, Toivo produced his truck keys. He looked down at me. “Are you ready?”
I shouldered the straps of my backpack and peered out at the writhing trees. The pressure in the air was building, the leaves turning. Carmi had mentioned it this morning, even before the winds had picked up. It was his special, unique demon sense to predict the weather, and I saw rain in his eyes when he watched the clouds form outside the window.
I never did like the feeling of an approaching storm.
“Yes,” I said. “Let’s go before Yuuhi blows away.”

